## 4. AI/ML detection engine

### Feature store — Feast

Splits **real-time features** (claim velocity, member geo-pattern, payment timing, device fingerprint, session behaviour, agent transaction velocity) from **batch features** (provider history, hospital tariff benchmarks, seasonal fraud patterns, ICD-10-IN code distribution).

### Ensemble model pipeline

| Model | Role | Strength |
|---|---|---|
| **XGBoost** | Tabular | Structured features, SHAP explainability |
| **LightGBM** | Tabular | High-cardinality categoricals, leaf-wise growth |
| **PyTorch** | Neural | Embeddings, text sequences, graph structures |

A **blender** (weighted average → stacking → logistic meta-learner) produces the final **FIQ Score (0–100)** with risk-tier mapping and explainability output.

*Why ensemble over a single model:* reduces overfitting and improves generalization across India's demographic diversity — a single model trained on one region's claim patterns generalizes poorly nationwide.

### Graph analytics — Neo4j

Node types: Member, Provider, Hospital, Agent, Claim, Device, Address.
Relationship types: TREATED_AT, REFERRED_BY, BILLED_BY, AGENT_FOR, LINKED_TO, SAME_AS, RELATED_TO.

Detection patterns: collusion rings (hospital–doctor–agent triangles), claim shopping (one member → multiple insurers), ghost agenting (agent → many members, no consent), provider billing spikes (sudden 300% MoM), device clustering (multiple enrolments from one IP).

*Why graph is essential in India:* Indian healthcare fraud is frequently organized rather than opportunistic. Hospital–doctor–agent rings are invisible to per-claim scoring but obvious as graph structures.

### Anomaly detection

Isolation Forest (unsupervised outliers), deep autoencoders (reconstruction error / latent-space anomaly), and **seasonal decomposition** for festival health-claim spikes, crop-insurance seasonality, and monsoon motor claims.

*Why seasonal decomposition:* Indian insurance has strong, predictable seasonal patterns that a naïve anomaly detector would mis-flag as fraud.

