## 5. Clinical cross-match engine (India-adapted)

Inputs: bill (UB-04 / CMS-1500 equivalents), physician progress notes, lab reports, drug chart.

The cross-match engine performs line-item tracing, temporal logic, dose-vs-lab checks, and impossible-value detection, then scores against four India-specific references:

| Check | India reference | What it catches |
|---|---|---|
| **CGHS package-rate compare** | Govt-notified CGHS rates, state-wise tariff | Overbilling vs benchmark |
| **NABH audit-trail verify** | NABH certificate validity, accreditation level | Accreditation fraud |
| **ICD-10-IN coding audit** | Indian ICD-10 modifications | Upcoding, unbundling, phantom billing |
| **NPPA drug-price check** | NPPA ceiling prices, Jan Aushadhi rates | Drug overpricing |

*Why this differs from the US:* US pricing is DRG-based; India uses government-notified package rates (CGHS) and NPPA ceilings. NABH is the closest Indian equivalent to Joint Commission certification. ICD-10-IN includes Indian modifications for tropical diseases and malnutrition codes.

Output conflict flags include bill-vs-notes mismatch, dose-vs-labs mismatch, impossible vitals, and duplicate billing.

